The correct graph is $ans1.  We can tell from the graph that the vertex of \( \ f(x) = x^2 \) has been moved, so there must be vertical and/or horizontal shifts performed in order to get the graph of \( \ h(x) \) in graph $ans1.  Since the vertex of \( \ h(x) \) is at ($h, $k), we can tell there has been a horizontal shift to the left by $h_abs units.  $vert_exp
$BR $SPACE $BR
Since the graph opens $updown , there $ans3 been a reflection over the $BITALIC x${EITALIC}-axis.  We should expect there to be a vertical stretch or compression since \( x^2 \) term has an $a in front of it.  We can tell that since \( \ $a_abs > 1 \) there has been a vertical stretch by a factor of $a_abs.
$BR $SPACE $BR
If complete the square, we can write the equation for \( \ h(x) \) in vertex form as follows, \( \ \ h(x) = $a (x-$h)^2 + $k \) $SPACE and determine all of the shifts without the graph as well.
